RamJam recently launched 'Southern Rail Tycoon' on Thursday, attracting 45,000 players to its satirical gameplay. In this light-hearted game, the objective is to prevent guards from boarding trains. Succeeding in this leads to service cancellations, from which players 'profit' by collecting virtual fares. The game draws its inspiration from the persistent train cancellations experienced over recent months, a result of an ongoing dispute with the RMT union. Players lose when a sufficient number of guards successfully board a train, causing the delayed service to finally depart.

Tom Jackson, a developer based in Brighton, shared his personal frustration, recounting how a planned trip to London a month prior was repeatedly delayed and then ultimately cancelled, leading his group to abandon train travel altogether. This frustrating experience prompted Mr. Jackson and his colleagues, Phil Hart and Toby Funnell, to create the game. The 39-year-old developer explained that the game serves a dual purpose: offering a fun distraction for commuters enduring train delays and raising awareness about the available compensation policies. Upon game completion, links are provided to Southern Rail's official compensation page and their Twitter account.

Jackson further elaborated that their studio enjoys creating games that are "reactive" to current events, demonstrating the "impact" news has on individuals. He described the train service as "an absolute shambles" and "incredibly frustrating".

A spokesperson for Southern Rail countered, stating that cancelling trains actually results in financial losses for them. They expressed efforts to provide the "best service possible under very difficult circumstances" and offered a "sincere apology".

The root of the ongoing issue lies in a dispute between the RMT union and GTR concerning the proposed increase in driver-only operated (DOO) services, which would alter the responsibilities of conductors. Due to regular strikes, Southern cancelled 341 daily train services on July 11, citing a need to improve "reliability." Since then, 15 of these services have been reinstated.

The continuous delays on the line, managed by Govia Thameslink Railway, led to the resignation of Rail Minister Claire Perry last Friday. The new Transport Secretary, Chris Grayling, declared on Monday that resolving the strike action was "top of his priority list".

Cormack is confident that, working together and with fan support, they can enhance the club's financial standing, enlarge its supporter base, and develop a modern community stadium and training complex, enabling AFC to effectively leverage developments in European club competitions. Chairman Stewart Milne expressed his welcome for Cormack's engagement and the wealth of experience he brings. During his Open Championship debut at Royal Birkdale, 38-year-old Manley briefly held the lead, achieving a two-under-par score despite the challenging weather. A pleased Manley conveyed to BBC Radio Wales that he had initially considered par to be a respectable outcome for his first attempt. He concluded his round impressively, scoring an eagle three on the par-five 17th and a birdie on the final hole. Manley remarked that ending the round a couple of strokes under par felt 'great'. This strong finish marked a significant recovery from a nervous beginning, where he lost a stroke on the first hole after his opening drive at one of golf's major tournaments landed in the rough. He described feeling extremely anxious on the first tee, admitting he was 'shaking a little bit' due to the 'horrific' weather. He also mentioned difficulties warming up and a lack of rhythm while wearing his waterproof gear. Manley confessed it was likely the 'most nervous' he had ever been for a tee shot, but expressed optimism about understanding what to anticipate for the next day, hinting at a 'better game plan'. Most of My Local's stores, specifically 93 out of 125, are set to close. The remaining outlets will stay open while KPMG, the appointed administrator, seeks potential buyers. Should these efforts fail, those stores too will cease operations. The company had a workforce of 1,658 individuals.

Morrisons, a supermarket chain, sold My Local to Greybull Capital last year and has since committed to offering positions to former My Local employees. The retailer found it difficult to compete in the fiercely competitive and price-war-ridden grocery market.

Formerly known as Morrisons' M Local, My Local was acquired by Greybull for £25 million. This acquisition was spearheaded by Mike Greene, an experienced figure in retail who gained public recognition from his appearance on Channel 4's The Secret Millionaire.

My Local had indicated earlier this month that administrators were alerted to assume control of the business. Just last week, Morrisons extended a helping hand to My Local's staff, proposing job opportunities within its own supermarkets in the event of store closures.

Mike Greene expressed his regret, stating that the past nine months constituted "one of the toughest retail trading periods" he had ever encountered, with My Local confronting "intense competition." He added that the management team was "unable to return the business to profitability," for which he was "truly sorry."

Mark Orton, a partner at KPMG and joint administrator, commented that the management faced "tough trading conditions," and despite their "best efforts to improve performance," My Local ultimately "was unable to return to viability." He confirmed that while most stores have now ceased operations, KPMG is engaged in "active discussions with a number of interested parties" regarding both the 32 remaining operational premises and a select few that have already shut down.

My Local's collapse highlights a challenging period for the retail industry, coming after the bankruptcies of BHS and Austin Reed. Furthermore, on Tuesday, the owners of Store Twenty One, a fashion retailer, announced plans for a restructuring that could lead to store closures and job cuts.

A study published in the Journal of Aesthetic Nursing reveals a rising inclination among individuals under 25 to receive anti-wrinkle injections. However, the findings indicate that such "frozen faces" might impede young people's ability to fully develop emotional expression. A prominent UK plastic surgery association deems the cosmetic use of Botox in teenagers to be "morally wrong." Botox, and similar neurotoxins, function by temporarily immobilizing muscles in the upper facial region, thereby diminishing wrinkles that appear during frowning.

Helen Collier, the nurse practitioner who conducted this research, attributes young people's aspiration for an "inexpressive frozen face" to the influence of reality television and celebrity culture. She highlights the widely recognized psychological concept of the facial feedback hypothesis, which posits that adolescents acquire social interaction skills by imitating others' facial expressions. Collier states that "our capacity as human beings to exhibit a broad spectrum of emotions is highly reliant on facial expressions." She adds that "emotions like empathy and sympathy are vital for our survival and for developing into self-assured, communicative adults." Nevertheless, she cautions that an increasing number of young individuals with "blank-faced" appearances might impair their capability to accurately express feelings. She warns, "Eliminating these expressions could impede their emotional and social maturation."

The study advocates for medical professionals to employ assessment instruments to determine if there are clear clinical justifications for administering Botox. While various assessment scales exist, evaluating factors such as skin thickness, sun damage, and wrinkle depth, experts caution that certain Botox clinics prioritize financial profit over patient well-being. Ms. Collier encourages therapists to devote time to enhancing young people's self-confidence instead of resorting to injections. She further states that "although the majority of the toxin's effects are temporary, studies indicate that muscles may not fully recover from the injections." She stresses, "It is crucial to comprehend the repercussions of initiating treatments at too young an age."

Dr. Michael Lewis, a psychology researcher at Cardiff University, explains that "the expressions we form on our faces influence the emotions we experience." He elaborates, "We smile due to happiness, yet smiling also generates happiness." He concludes that "medications like Botox inhibit a patient's ability to create specific expressions, potentially impacting our natural process of learning to feel emotions." Rajiv Grover, president of the British Association of Aesthetic Plastic Surgeons, asserts that "administering Botox to teenagers for cosmetic reasons is ethically indefensible and something no responsible practitioner would undertake." He warns, "This practice can only intensify body image concerns during a sensitive developmental period." Ms. Collier's findings are scheduled to be presented at the Clinical Cosmetic and Reconstructive Expo in October.
